Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Remove and discard any large stems from @kale{4%ounce}. Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%can}.

Place kale and chickpeas in a large #bowl{}. Toss with @garlic powder{1%tsp}, half the @veggie stock concentrate{2} (use half), a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread kale and chickpeas out in a single layer on a foil-lined #baking sheet{}. Roast on top rack until slightly crispy, stirring halfway through, ~{18-22%minutes}.

> For 4 servings, divide kale and chickpeas between two baking sheets and roast on top and middle racks, swapping rack positions halfway through.

Wipe out bowl.

Meanwhile, in a small #pot{} (medium pot for 4 servings), combine @Israeli couscous{5%ounce}, remaining stock concentrate, and @water{1 1/4%cups}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}.

In bowl used for kale and chickpeas, whisk together @red pepper jam{1%unit}, half the @red wine vinegar{5%tsp}, @olive oil{1%tbsp}, and a pinch of salt and pepper until thoroughly combined.

To bowl with dressing, add tomatoes and @dried apricots{1%ounce}. Toss to combine.

Transfer roasted kale and chickpeas and cooked couscous to bowl. Toss to combine; season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide roasted kale and chickpea couscous between bowls and top with @sliced almonds{1/2%ounce}. Serve.

> Buckle up, buttercup, because this power bowl is a brawny one! We present a veritable one-bowl feast that's bursting with flavors and textures.